commit.message:
Refactor of delegate.od

`delegate.od` is the third-largest
[redo](https://github.com/apenwarr/redo)-related file in the
repository, and contains considerably more
complexity(/generality) than `_config.od.in` or
`libwvbase.list.do`.  Following some redo mailing list
discussion, this is my attempt to decompose it into independent
functions.

Fix unit test failures when compiled with -NDEBUG.

Reported-by: Nathan Myers

configure: improved way of detecting if redo is installed.

Previously, we'd give the same error no matter why redo returned a
non-zero exit code, which could be for a variety of reasons, but we
redirected output to stderr, so redo couldn't report which one.
Instead, detect whether there is a runnable 'redo' command at all, and
only print our warning message if not.

Reported-by: Nathan Myers

Removed an incorrect "exec >&2" at the top of delegate.od.

This was inherited by all sub-.do files, which is a bit dangerous
(although they're all written to not rely on stdout anyway).

delegate.od: update to new-style redo-whichdo output.

Formerly required redo-0.20.  Now it'll require redo-0.21 or later.
delegate.od: avoid a bashism.

Remove call to -Wl,-Map in link.od.

Works with GNU binutils, but not on MacOS with llvm.  I was just using
this temporarily for debugging anyway.

link.od was always linking against libwvstatic.so.

Instead, the script that calls link.od needs to add the right wvstreams
libraries to the objs= variable.
Fix unitest.sh for win32.

Fix some bugs leading to win32 test failures.

Mostly, win32/*.o weren't being included at all.  It probably should
not have even linked successfully, except we're doing a few too many
tricks in win32/streams.cc, including generating our own versions of
read() and write() that try to override the libc versions.  If we don't
link them in... the program still links, but it doesn't work.

Realistically we should probably call those functions something
different, and define the Unix version as a simple wrapper that calls
libc read() and write().

Remove hardcoded wvports-related paths in Windows builds.

Instead, you should pass --with-zlib=$PWD/.... etc directly, to specify
paths to any dependencies you might have built elsewhere.  This is what
the wvbuild project was already doing when building wvstreams, but the
presents of the wvports-related specific paths was hiding a bug in our
implementation of the --with_zlib parameter.

Fix several warnings, including -Wextra warnings.

I don't know about -Wunused-parameter though: it doesn't seem to help
anyone to whine about unused parameters in functions that are going to
be overloaded anyway, so I've disabled that warning for now.

compile.do: remove sed and xargs from autodepends steps.

Past-me knew a better way to do it, that I put in the redo README.
Let's use that method :)

Remove unnecessary && and 'exec >&2' paranoia from .do files.

I had forgotten that apenwarr/redo always calls with 'sh -e', so sh
scripts will abort after the first error anyway.  And redo also gives a
useful error message if you write to stdout *and* $3, so we don't have
to be so defensive about redirecting stdout all the time.

This makes the scripts a little more readable, and thus more suitable
to use as redo examples.

Convert 'install' targets from make to redo.

install-shlibs: install lib*.so.*
install-dev: install lib*.so, lib*.a, and include headers
install-uniconfd: install uniconfd daemon and uni client

Merge build system changes from wvbuild project.

* commit '2a6b25f31814f372201516521a2479ee4de2d09e':
  Overhaul wvstreams build system from Makefiles to redo.
  Remove support for boost/function.hpp in favour of tr1/functional.
  wvstreams.supp: remove as libc6 and openssl are nowadays valgrind-clean.
  Fix compilation under mingw64; wvtestmain runs under wine64.

Overhaul wvstreams build system from Makefiles to redo.

This fixes a bunch of dependency problems, allows better parallelism,
and lets us remove a lot of obsolete cruft.

Remove support for boost/function.hpp in favour of tr1/functional.

tr1/functional is *also* obsolete, but compilers on Linux and MacOS,
and mingw32 cross compilers on Linux, are all new enough to have it, so
boost is never needed.

Someday we should migrate this stuff to c++11 instead.

wvstreams.supp: remove as libc6 and openssl are nowadays valgrind-clean.

We can also remove README.TESTS, which only existed to explain how to
make and use a custom valgrind-clean openssl.

Fix compilation under mingw64; wvtestmain runs under wine64.

The bad news is there are lots of test failures.  The good news is
there are also quite a lot of test passes, so it's probably fairly
tractable.

Merge win32 and MacOS support fixes from wvbuild repo.

* commit '93f9937445ae136704eadb7e59605b70c77afdbe':
  unitest.sh: don't expect to run from WVSTREAMS/uniconf/tests anymore.
  wvtestmain: call gethostbyname() before counting fds.
  Disable crypt_md5 on MacOS.
  wvpushdir.h: Fix valgrind free/delete mismatch error.
  wvpushdir.t failed when /tmp was a symlink.
  Reduce timeouts in uniretrygen.t so tests run faster.
  Fix bad use of temporary WvString object in unireplicategen.t.cc.
  Rewrite wvprociter to use 'ps' instead of /proc.
  Fix WvShmZone for MacOS.
  WvUnixAddr: calculate sockaddr_len more conservatively.
  wvunixdgsocket.t: don't send more than 2048 bytes, the MacOS limit.
  wvsslstream.t.cc was timing-sensitive on MacOS.
  Change WvTask back to setjmp/longjmp.
  WvRegex::seterr() accessed preg even when it was invalid.
  wvstreams: explicitly link with -ldl.
  Fix compilation on MacOS using llvm.

unitest.sh: don't expect to run from WVSTREAMS/uniconf/tests anymore.

This caused problems with LD_LIBRARY_PATH on modern MacOS, which is
apparently ultra picky about which library path can be used where,
thanks to "system integrity protection."  Apparently it's okay to use
LD_LIBRARY_PATH=., although that won't be inherited by shell scripts,
so we have to set it inside unitest.sh itself.

Internet advice suggests we link our libraries and programs using an
Rpath containing $ORIGIN instead, so that test programs can find their
.so files using a relative path.  That sounds good, and looks like it
would work on seemingly any ELF-using system.  I don't want to make it
in this commit though because it might involve major Makefile surgery.

wvtestmain: call gethostbyname() before counting fds.

Activating the resolver on MacOS leaks a file descriptor, so lt's make
sure to do that before counting file descriptors.

Disable crypt_md5 on MacOS.

It was compiling okay, but actually still using DES encryption.  To
their credit, this caused the unit tests to fail.  But leave it out of
the library since it's not actually available on that platform.

wvpushdir.h: Fix valgrind free/delete mismatch error.

I don't know why I didn't get this error before, and am frankly quite
worried about that.
wvpushdir.t failed when /tmp was a symlink.
Reduce timeouts in uniretrygen.t so tests run faster.
Fix bad use of temporary WvString object in unireplicategen.t.cc.

Rewrite wvprociter to use 'ps' instead of /proc.

This should be more compatible across unix systems, and not much
slower.

Fix WvShmZone for MacOS.

It doesn't like mapping /dev/zero, but we can MAP_ANON on fd==-1
instead.

This uncovered some error propagation bugs inside some related classes,
so fix those too.
